 medicine","phonetic":"TAYK-this-MED-i-sin","emoji":"💊","audio_ref":null},"long_ago":{"word":"A long time ago","literal":"Long ago","phonetic":"a-LONG-TAIM-uh-GOH","emoji":"⏳","audio_ref":null},"once_upon_a_time":{"word":"Once upon a time...","literal":"Once upon a time / there was...","phonetic":"WUNS-uh-PON-a-TAIM","emoji":"📖","audio_ref":null},"i_used_to_be":{"word":"I used to be...","literal":"I used to be...","phonetic":"ai-YOOST-to-BEE","emoji":"🕰️","audio_ref":null},"hope":{"word":"Hope","literal":"Hope","phonetic":"HOPE","emoji":"🌅","audio_ref":null},"i_hope_for":{"word":"I hope to...","literal":"I hope for / expect...","phonetic":"ai-HOPE-to","emoji":"🤞","audio_ref":null},"the_future":{"word":"The future","literal":"The future / tomorrow","phonetic":"thuh-FYOO-chur","emoji":"🚀","audio_ref":null},"proverb_unity":{"word":"United we stand, divided we fall","literal":"A unity proverb","phonetic":"yoo-NAI-ted-wee-STAND","emoji":"🤝","audio_ref":null},"proverb_relationship_food":{"word":"Breaking bread together makes friends","literal":"A food-and-friendship proverb","phonetic":"BRAY-king-BRED-tu-GETH-ur","emoji":"🥣","audio_ref":null},"proverb_hard_work":{"word":"Hard work pays off","literal":"A hard-work proverb","phonetic":"HARD-WURK-payz-OFF","emoji":"🧹","audio_ref":null},"i_have_arrived":{"word":"I've arrived","literal":"I have arrived","phonetic":"AIV-uh-RAIVD","emoji":"🏁","audio_ref":null},"i_keep_going_forward":{"word":"I keep moving forward","literal":"I keep going forward","phonetic":"ai-KEEP-MOO-ving-FOR-wurd","emoji":"🚀","audio_ref":null},"journey_continues":{"word":"The journey continues","literal":"The journey continues","phonetic":"thuh-JUR-nee-kun-TIN-yooz","emoji":"🛤️","audio_ref":null}}$$::jsonb,
  $${"m01-l01":{"title":"Hello — Your First English Greetings","hook":"In English-speaking cultures, 'Hello' is the universal opener. It works in a boardroom and on a street corner. But native speakers shift between Hello, Hi, Hey, and time-of-day greetings without thinking — and that fluency is what we'll build today.","cultural_note":"English greetings are unusually flexible. Unlike Shona's tsika-rooted wellness checks or Japanese's strict formality tiers, English mostly encodes closeness through tone and word choice rather than separate greeting forms. 'Hi' to your boss is fine in most cultures; 'Hey' starts to feel casual. We'll learn the safe defaults that work everywhere."},"m01-l02":{"title":"Hi & Bye — Casual English Greetings","hook":"Hi! Today we learn the words used between friends — 'Hi' and 'Bye'. These are casual, warm, and used everywhere from London to Lagos.","cultural_note":"In English-speaking cultures, 'Hi' is acceptable to almost everyone, including strangers — unlike some languages where casualness can feel disrespectful. 'Hey' is a step more familiar, used between friends. When in doubt, 'Hi' is always safe."},"m01-l03":{"title":"Good Morning in English","hook":"Good morning. In English, asking 'Did you sleep well?' shows care — much like Shona's 'Marara sei?'. But English speakers usually open with just 'Good morning' and let the wellness check follow if at all.","cultural_note":"In English-speaking workplaces, 'Good morning' is the standard until around noon. 'Did you sleep well?' is more often used between intimates or hosts to overnight guests. Don't expect it as routine the way Shona's morning wellness check is routine."},"m01-l04":{"title":"Good Afternoon in English","hook":"Good afternoon! When the day reaches midday, English greetings shift from 'Good morning' to 'Good afternoon' — exactly the way Mangwanani / Masikati shift in Shona, but the cutoff is 12pm sharp.","cultural_note":"In English-speaking cultures, 'Good afternoon' is more formal than 'Hi'. People often opt for casual 'How's your day?' instead — soft, friendly, doesn't require a real answer. It's small talk, not a wellness check."},"m01-l05":{"title":"Good Evening in English","hook":"Good evening! After about 5pm, English greetings shift to 'Good evening'. Common in shops, restaurants, and hotels — anywhere there's customer service.","cultural_note":"In English-speaking countries, 'How was your day?' is the warm version of an evening greeting — typical between partners coming home from work, or close friends. Compare with Shona's 'Maswera sei?', which is more universally expected."},"m01-l06":{"title":"What's Your Name? in English","hook":"Hi! To get to know someone in English, you start with the name. Ask 'What's your name?' and reply with 'My name is ...'. Then add 'Nice to meet you' once names are exchanged.","cultural_note":"In English-speaking cultures, exchanging names early in a conversation is the norm — even between strangers in casual settings. It's expected and not pushy. Compare to Shona, where giving your name to a stranger without context can feel forward."},"m01-l07":{"title":"Where Are You From? in English","hook":"Hello! In English, when asking about origin, you use 'from' (place of origin) or 'in' (current residence). 'Where are you from?' asks origin; 'I live in...' is current.","cultural_note":"In English, 'from' indicates where you grew up or were born; 'in' indicates where you currently live. So you can be 'from Harare' but 'living in London'. This distinction matters in English in a way it doesn't in Shona."},"m01-l08":{"title":"Polite \"How are you?\" in English","hook":"Hello! English has casual greetings and formal ones. At work, with elders, or in formal interviews, you might use 'How do you do?' rather than 'How are you?'.","cultural_note":"In English, 'How do you do?' is now somewhat dated but still works in formal settings — interviews, business meetings, formal introductions. Modern English uses 'Pleased to meet you' more commonly. 'How are you?' has become so casual it's often answered with 'Good, you?' without much thought."},"m01-l09":{"title":"Goodbye in English","hook":"Hello! Saying goodbye in English has many flavours: formal 'Goodbye', plan-based 'See you tomorrow', and warm 'Take care'.","cultural_note":"In English, 'Take care' carries genuine warmth — like Shona's 'Famba zvakanaka' (go well). It's used between friends, family, and people you genuinely care about — not in formal contexts. Use it for closeness, not formality."},"m01-l10":{"title":"The English Greeting Conversation","hook":"Hi! Today we review everything from Module 1 — from 'Hello' to 'Goodbye'. A complete first-meeting in English.","cultural_note":"An English-language first encounter is typically faster than a Shona one. Greeting → name exchange → light small talk → goodbye can happen in 60 seconds at a coffee shop. Don't be surprised by the pace — it doesn't mean lack of warmth, just different conventions."},"m02-l01":{"title":"Please in English","hook":"Hi! Module 2 starts with survival phrases — words that help when you're stuck or unsure. First up: 'Please', 'Excuse me', 'Sorry'.","cultural_note":"In English-speaking cultures, 'Please' is sprinkled liberally — even for trivial requests. Skipping it can sound abrupt or rude, especially in British English. 'Please' softens almost any request and is rarely overused."},"m02-l02":{"title":"Thank You in English","hook":"Hi! Today we learn gratitude in English. 'Thank you' is the equivalent of 'Ndatenda', but the response 'You're welcome' has no exact Shona match.","cultural_note":"In English, people say 'Thank you' frequently — for opening a door, passing a dish, even routine service. Reply with 'You're welcome' or 'No problem'. Both are warm; 'You're welcome' is slightly more formal."},"m02-l03":{"title":"Can You Help Me? in English","hook":"Hi! When you're lost or unsure, you need to ask for help. In English, 'Can you...?' is a soft, polite way to make a request.","cultural_note":"In English, 'Can you help me?' is informal but polite. 'Could you help me?' is even softer. 'Would you mind helping me?' is the most polite. Don't worry — even shopkeepers and strangers respond warmly to a clear 'Can you help me?'."},"m02-l04":{"title":"Do You Speak English? in English","hook":"Hi! Before starting a conversation with a stranger, it's polite to ask 'Do you speak English?'. The question starts with 'Do' — that's the English question pattern.","cultural_note":"In English, factual questions usually start with 'Do' or 'Does'. Just saying 'You speak English?' (rising tone) is acceptable in fast casual speech but isn't standard. The 'Do you...' pattern is one to internalise — it appears constantly."},"m02-l05":{"title":"I Don't Understand in English","hook":"Hi! Whenever you don't understand, say so. In English: 'I don't understand'. This is your shield against confusion.","cultural_note":"English negation uses 'don't' (do + not). 'I don't understand' isn't shameful — English speakers expect language learners to use it, and most will happily slow down or rephrase. Don't smile and nod when you're lost."},"m02-l06":{"title":"Yes & No in English","hook":"Hi! Two simple words but essential: Yes and No. Add 'Maybe' when you're unsure.","cultural_note":"In English, 'Yes' is firmly affirmative — it commits. Saying 'Yes' politely when you mean 'Maybe' is considered slightly dishonest. If unsure, say 'Maybe' or 'Let me think about it'. English values commitment in answers."},"m02-l07":{"title":"Where Is...? in English","hook":"Hi! To find a place or thing, ask 'Where is...?'. This question opens up navigating any new place — from finding the bathroom to the exit.","cultural_note":"In English, the question structure goes: 'Where' + 'is' + 'the' + thing. Note the 'the' — most things in English need it. 'Where is the bathroom?' (correct) vs. 'Where is bathroom?' (sounds like a translation)."},"m02-l08":{"title":"How Much? in English","hook":"Hi! At a market or shop, you'll need to ask the price. In English: 'How much?'. Add 'It's expensive' or 'It's cheap' to start bargaining.","cultural_note":"Bargaining in English-speaking markets varies wildly. UK supermarkets — never. London craft markets — sometimes. US flea markets — yes. Saying 'It's expensive' with a smile signals friendly negotiation. In a department store? It signals confusion."},"m02-l09":{"title":"Emergency Phrases in English","hook":"Hi! Hopefully you'll never need these — but if you do, they need to come fast. 'Help!', 'Call the police', 'I need a doctor'.","cultural_note":"In English-speaking countries, emergency services are usually summoned with a call to a national number — 999 (UK), 911 (US/Canada), 000 (Australia). Shouting 'Help!' in a crowd will draw attention; staff and bystanders are trained to respond to clear, loud English."},"m02-l10":{"title":"Survival in English Conversation","hook":"Hi! You've finished Module 2 — the survival kit for English. Today we combine everything: 'Excuse me', 'Please', 'I don't understand', 'Where is...?', 'Thank you'.","cultural_note":"In English-speaking situations, brief politeness (please / thank you / excuse me) goes a long way. Long, elaborate politeness — common in some other cultures — can actually slow down communication. Be polite, but be concise."},"m03-l01":{"title":"I Am... in English","hook":"Hi! Today we learn how to introduce yourself in English. The key phrase: 'I am' — or contracted, 'I'm'. This is how you tell people your name, job, or origin.","cultural_note":"In English, the verb 'am' must always be present — unlike Shona where 'Ndini' carries it implicitly. 'I'm a teacher' is correct; 'I teacher' sounds incomplete. The auxiliary verb is grammatically required in English."},"m03-l02":{"title":"How Old Are You? in English","hook":"Hi! Asking age in English is straightforward, but be aware that adults — especially women — can find the question intrusive. Best for forms, doctors, or close friends.","cultural_note":"In English-speaking countries, asking adults their age can feel intrusive — especially women in social contexts. Many older people answer with 'I'm in my forties' rather than a specific number. Reading the social context matters more than the grammar."},"m03-l03":{"title":"What Do You Do? in English","hook":"Hi! 'What do you do?' in English asks about your job — not your current activity. Reply with 'I'm a teacher' or 'I work in IT'.","cultural_note":"In English, 'I'm a teacher' (with 'a') is correct — 'I'm teacher' sounds incorrect. The 'a' is an article, a small but essential word. English requires articles before professions. Get used to inserting them automatically."},"m03-l04":{"title":"Married? Children? in English","hook":"Hi! In English-speaking cultures, asking strangers about marriage or children can feel intrusive — but in family or close-friend contexts, it's normal. Today we learn how to answer.","cultural_note":"In English, 'married' applies to husbands and wives equally. 'I have two children' works for any parent. But the question 'Are you married?' can feel personal — many English speakers ask 'Do you have a partner?' to be more inclusive."},"m03-l05":{"title":"Hobbies in English","hook":"Hi! Hobbies — books, music, sports? In English, you say 'I like ...' or 'I enjoy ...'. After 'like' or 'enjoy', verbs take an '-ing' ending.","cultural_note":"In English, after 'like' or 'enjoy', verbs usually add '-ing': 'I like reading', 'I enjoy cooking'. 'I like to read' also works. The '-ing' form turns the verb into a noun-like form. This pattern is everywhere in casual conversation."},"m03-l06":{"title":"Languages I Speak — In English","hook":"Hi! In Zimbabwe many people speak two or three languages — Shona, Ndebele, English. Today we learn how to share that in English: 'I speak Shona', 'A little English', 'And some others'.","cultural_note":"In English, language names are capitalised — English, Shona, French. Saying 'a little English' is an act of humility, signalling you're still learning. English speakers often reply with encouragement, not criticism."},"m03-l07":{"title":"Where I Live in English","hook":"Hi! Today we say where you live and grew up in English. 'I live in...' (now), 'I grew up in...' (past), 'for ten years' (duration).","cultural_note":"In English, 'I live in Harare' is correct — never 'I live at Harare'. 'In' is used for cities and countries. 'Grew up' is past simple of 'grow up'. Past simple appears constantly in life narratives — internalise it."},"m03-l08":{"title":"Describing Yourself in English","hook":"Hi! What kind of person are you? Friendly? Shy? In English: 'I'm friendly', 'I'm shy sometimes', 'I love learning'. These adjectives let you describe yourself without bragging.","cultural_note":"In English-speaking cultures — especially in job interviews — saying 'I'm friendly' or 'I'm hardworking' is expected, not arrogant. This is a cultural difference from Shona, where self-praise can seem boastful. In English contexts, modest self-promotion is the norm."},"m03-l09":{"title":"Asking About Them in English","hook":"Hi! Good conversation goes both ways. After answering questions, ask back: 'Tell me about yourself', 'What's your story?', 'Where did you grow up?'.","cultural_note":"In English, 'Tell me about yourself' is a classic interview opener — formal but friendly. 'What's your story?' is more personal, used between friends. 'Where did you grow up?' uses past simple — grew up — which signals childhood."},"m03-l10":{"title":"Full English Introduction Conversation","hook":"Hi! Today we combine Module 3 — name, job, family, hobbies, languages, residence, and asking back. A complete first conversation in English.","cultural_note":"An English first-meeting conversation typically lasts 2-3 minutes — not too short, not too long. Make sure you exchange — not just deliver. This balance is the rhythm of English social and professional meetings."},"m04-l01":{"title":"A vs An in English","hook":"In English, before most singular nouns, you must add 'a' or 'an'. Shona doesn't have these — but English needs them.","cultural_note":"English has 'articles' — 'a', 'an', 'the' — that don't exist in Shona. Use 'a' before consonant sounds (a book), 'an' before vowel sounds (an apple). It's a habit you'll need to build. Think of 'a/an' as a kind of prefix English requires."},"m04-l02":{"title":"The — When to Use It","hook":"'The' refers to something specific or known. Shona doesn't have a direct equivalent — context carries that meaning instead.","cultural_note":"Shona uses context to indicate definiteness — if you say 'bhuku' and we both know which book, no extra word is needed. In English, you must say 'THE book' to mean the specific one. 'A book' = any book; 'The book' = the one we know."},"m04-l03":{"title":"No Article — Plural & Abstract","hook":"Sometimes English uses no article at all — for plurals (in general) and abstract concepts (love, time, music).","cultural_note":"Shona has no articles. English has them sometimes — but not always. 'Love' = 'rudo' (no article). 'Children' (in general) = no article. This sometimes-yes-sometimes-no pattern can be confusing — read example sentences until you feel the pattern."},"m04-l04":{"title":"Plurals in English — Adding -s","hook":"In English, most plurals just add '-s'. Cat → cats. Day → days. Friend → friends. Simpler than Shona's noun classes.","cultural_note":"Shona changes the prefix (mu → va, ru → ma). English just adds '-s' to the end of the word. While Shona is grammatically richer for plurals, English is operationally simpler — fewer rules to remember."},"m04-l05":{"title":"Irregular Plurals in English","hook":"Some words don't follow the '-s' rule. Child → children. Man → men. Foot → feet. They must be memorised individually.","cultural_note":"Shona also has irregular changes — so you understand grammar can have surprises. English irregular plurals just have to be memorised. There's no logical pattern. 'Child' becomes 'children', not 'childs'."},"m04-l06":{"title":"This & That, These & Those in English","hook":"'This' = near. 'That' = far. Plural: 'these' and 'those'. Shona has similar concepts (iri, iyo, apa, apo) — but English ties them to singular/plural too.","cultural_note":"Shona uses iri, iyo, apa, apo for proximity. English ties demonstratives to singular/plural too: this/these (near) vs that/those (far). It's similar to Shona but with the extra layer of number agreement."},"m04-l07":{"title":"Some & Any in English","hook":"'Some' is for positive statements. 'Any' is for negatives and questions. A pattern to memorise.","cultural_note":"Shona uses mamwe, chero, or no word at all — context decides. English follows a strict rule: 'some' in positive statements/offers, 'any' in questions/negatives. New rule — but it's predictable."},"m04-l08":{"title":"Past & Future in English","hook":"Past tense: yesterday — adding '-ed' or using irregular forms (went, saw, ate). Future: 'will' or 'going to'.","cultural_note":"Shona embeds tense in the verb prefix (-aka- past, -cha- future). English uses extra words: 'will' for future, '-ed' or irregular forms for past. The past-irregular verbs (went, saw, had, was) just need to be memorised."},"m04-l09":{"title":"Asking Questions in English","hook":"Questions in English use 'do/does' or wh- words: what, who, when, where, why, how. Today: what, who, when.","cultural_note":"English questions often need an auxiliary verb (do, does, did) at the start. 'Do you eat sadza?' — the 'do' is mandatory in standard English. Question intonation alone (rising tone) is not enough in formal settings."},"m04-l10":{"title":"Articles in Real English Talk — Conversation Capstone","hook":"You've finished Module 4. Now use a/an/the, plurals, this/that/these/those, some/any, much/many — all in flowing conversation.","cultural_note":"English builds itself through articles. Native ears notice when they're missing or wrong. Mastering articles is a marker of moving from beginner to intermediate English — and it's something Shona speakers have to learn deliberately, since their native language doesn't have them."},"m05-l01":{"title":"Mother & Father in English","hook":"Hi! Module 5 is about family. We start with parents — 'Mother' and 'Father'. English uses simpler family vocabulary than Shona.","cultural_note":"In English, 'mother' and 'father' are formal — 'mum' (UK) / 'mom' (US) and 'dad' are warmer. There's no inherent honorific layer — respect is shown by tone, not separate words. Compare to Shona's 'Amai' and 'Baba' which carry tsika built in."},"m05-l02":{"title":"Brothers & Sisters in English","hook":"Hi! Now siblings. In Shona, you specify older/younger and same/cross gender. In English, it's just 'brother' and 'sister'.","cultural_note":"Shona has rich sibling vocabulary — mukoma (older same gender), munin'ina (younger same gender), hanzvadzi (cross gender). English has just two words: brother and sister. To specify, English adds 'older' or 'younger'. The richer Shona system loses information when translated."},"m05-l03":{"title":"Sons & Daughters in English","hook":"Hi! Children: son (boy), daughter (girl), children (plural). Remember from Module 4: 'children' is irregular — not 'childs'.","cultural_note":"In English, 'son' and 'daughter' stand alone — no 'boy son' needed. 'Child' / 'children' is gender-neutral and increasingly preferred when gender is unknown or unimportant."},"m05-l04":{"title":"Grandparents in English","hook":"Hi! Grandparents — wisdom of the family. In English: 'grandmother' and 'grandfather'. The 'grand-' prefix means 'one generation above'.","cultural_note":"English 'grandmother' and 'grandfather' don't carry the social weight that Shona's 'Mbuya' and 'Sekuru' do — those are honorifics extended to all elder women/men. In English, respect for grandparents is shown in tone and stories, not in the word itself."},"m05-l05":{"title":"Aunts & Uncles in English","hook":"Hi! Here you'll see the biggest gap between Shona and English. Shona distinguishes paternal and maternal, older and younger — English uses just 'aunt' and 'uncle'.","cultural_note":"Shona has tete (paternal aunt), maiguru/mainini (maternal aunts), babamukuru/babamunini (paternal uncles), sekuru (maternal uncle). English collapses all of these into 'aunt' or 'uncle'. To express the Shona distinctions, you must add words: 'my aunt — my father's sister'."},"m05-l06":{"title":"In-laws in English","hook":"Hi! Spouse's family — in English: 'mother-in-law', 'father-in-law'. The hyphenated '-in-law' literally means 'through marriage law'.","cultural_note":"English 'in-law' terms are functional — they identify the relationship through marriage. They lack the deep cultural taboos of Shona vamwene/vatezvara (e.g., not speaking the spouse's-parent's name aloud). Respect in English is contextual and verbal, not encoded in special vocabulary."},"m05-l07":{"title":"Friends as Family in English","hook":"Hi! Close friends can be like family. In English: 'best friend', 'close friends', 'like family'. These phrases carry deep affection.","cultural_note":"In English, 'They're like family to me' is a strong statement of love and trust — equivalent to Shona's 'shamwari yepamoyo'. English uses fewer words to encode this — but the meaning is identical."},"m05-l08":{"title":"Family Verbs in English — Visit, Call, Miss","hook":"Hi! Family takes verbs: visit, call, miss. Two simple ones first. 'Miss' is trickier — works differently from Shona.","cultural_note":"In English, 'I miss my mother' means 'I feel her absence'. The subject is 'I' — the missing one. In Shona 'ndakasuwa' similarly places the feeling in the speaker. The structure is parallel — but the verbs themselves are different."},"m05-l09":{"title":"Telling Family Stories in English","hook":"Hi! 'A long time ago...', 'My grandmother used to...', 'He always says...'. These are the storytelling phrases of English.","cultural_note":"English 'used to' (= vaisi in Shona) describes habitual past action that no longer happens. It's a key storytelling tool. 'My grandmother used to cook every Sunday' — meaning she did, but doesn't anymore."},"m05-l10":{"title":"A Family Conversation in English — Capstone","hook":"Hi! You've completed Module 5. Today: parents, siblings, children, grandparents, aunts/uncles, in-laws, friends, family verbs — all in one conversation.","cultural_note":"Talking about family in English is a fast bonding move — even more so when the speaker comes from a culture (like Shona) with rich family vocabulary. Using English to translate Shona richness ('my aunt — my father's sister') signals depth and helps your listener understand who you really are."},"m06-l01":{"title":"Numbers 1-10 in English","hook":"Hi! Module 6 starts with numbers — daily essentials. One through Ten in English.","cultural_note":"Shona numbers shift with noun class (vana vatatu = three children). English numbers are invariant — 'three' is 'three' before any noun: three children, three dollars, three days. One thing to memorise, no class agreement."},"m06-l02":{"title":"Numbers 11-100 in English","hook":"Hi! 11 to 100. English has a clean pattern: twenty, thirty, forty... combined with 1-9 for 'twenty-five', 'forty-seven'.","cultural_note":"Shona builds 'makumi maviri nemashanu' (two-tens-and-five = 25). English uses a hyphen: 'twenty-five'. Note the irregular ones: eleven, twelve, thirteen — they break the teen pattern. Memorise them."},"m06-l03":{"title":"Hundreds, Thousands, Millions in English","hook":"Hi! Larger numbers: thousand, million, billion. Useful for prices, salaries, populations.","cultural_note":"In English, 'thousand' stays singular when counted: 'two thousand dollars', not 'two thousands'. This rule is consistent: 'three million people', 'four hundred kilometres'. The number functions as an adjective."},"m06-l04":{"title":"What Time? in English","hook":"Hi! 'What time is it?' is asked daily. Reply: 'It's seven o'clock'.","cultural_note":"In English, 'o'clock' is short for 'of the clock' — an old expression that survives in modern speech. Use 24-hour or 12-hour formats; the UK and US prefer 12-hour with A.M./P.M. The 24-hour 'military time' is common in Europe and aviation."},"m06-l05":{"title":"Half Past, Quarter To in English","hook":"Hi! Now minutes. 'Half past two' (2:30), 'quarter to nine' (8:45), 'five past six' (6:05).","cultural_note":"In British English, 'half past two' = 2:30. American English often uses 'two thirty' — simpler, more direct. 'Quarter past' = 15 minutes after; 'quarter to' = 15 minutes before. Both styles work; pick what feels natural."},"m06-l06":{"title":"Days of the Week in English","hook":"Hi! Days of the week: Monday through Sunday. Note: starts with Monday in most English-speaking cultures, not Sunday.","cultural_note":"English day names come from old pagan gods (Wednesday = Woden's day, Thursday = Thor's day). Few modern speakers think about this. In English, day names are always capitalised — 'Monday', not 'monday'."},"m06-l07":{"title":"Months & Seasons in English","hook":"Hi! Months: January through December. Seasons: spring, summer, autumn (UK) / fall (US), winter. But Zimbabwe has rainy and dry seasons!","cultural_note":"English month names come from the Roman calendar — 'January' from Janus (god of doors). For southern-hemisphere speakers, summer is December-February while northern English speakers think summer is June-August. Mention the location: 'In Zimbabwe, our summer is December.'"},"m06-l08":{"title":"Money in English","hook":"Hi! Money in English — 'How much?', 'It costs $20', 'It's expensive'. These get you through any market or shop.","cultural_note":"Zimbabwe has used USD widely — 'dollar' and 'cent' are familiar to Shona speakers. In English-speaking countries you'll hear 'pounds' (UK), 'dollars' (US/Canada/Australia), 'rand' (SA). Bargaining culture varies wildly: market — yes; supermarket — never."},"m06-l09":{"title":"Numbers in Shopping in English","hook":"Hi! Shopping numbers: 'Two for ten dollars', 'discount', 'total'. These help you save money and verify the bill.","cultural_note":"On a receipt: 'subtotal' (before tax), 'tax' (VAT in UK, sales tax in US), 'total' (final amount). 'Discount' or 'sale' indicates a price reduction. Most non-market English-speaking shops have fixed prices — bargaining is unusual."},"m06-l10":{"title":"Money & Time Conversation Capstone in English","hook":"Hi! You've finished Module 6. Now: numbers 1-million, time, days, months, money — all woven into one conversation.","cultural_note":"In English, numbers and time appear in nearly every transactional moment — kombi fares, supermarket totals, WhatsApp scheduling, work meetings. Mastering them in English unlocks the practical layer of life in any English-speaking country."},"m07-l01":{"title":"Hungry & Thirsty in English","hook":"Hi! Module 7 covers food. We start with two universal experiences: hunger and thirst.","cultural_note":"In English-speaking cultures, saying 'I'm hungry' to a host doesn't automatically trigger food being offered — unlike in many Shona homes. You may need to ask more directly or wait for offered food. Phrase it gently: 'I'm a bit hungry' or 'I could eat'."},"m07-l02":{"title":"Common Foods in English","hook":"Hi! Today: bread, rice, meat. The basic foods you'll see on most menus in English-speaking countries.","cultural_note":"In English, 'meat' is generic — beef, chicken, pork are all 'meat'. Restaurants typically specify which animal. In English-speaking cities (London, Cape Town), menus are usually entirely in English, often with no Shona equivalent listed."},"m07-l03":{"title":"At a Restaurant in English","hook":"Hi! Restaurant phrases: 'a table for two', 'menu, please', 'the bill, please'. The basics for being seated, ordering, and paying.","cultural_note":"In English-speaking restaurants, you typically wait to be seated, then order from a menu, then pay at the end. Tipping varies: UK 12.5% often added automatically; US 18-20% expected; Zimbabwe largely tip-optional. Know the local convention."},"m07-l04":{"title":"Ordering Food in English","hook":"Hi! When ordering, English uses polite forms: 'I'd like...' (not 'I want...'), and you can request modifications: 'without onions'.","cultural_note":"In English-speaking restaurants, customisation is welcome — many people have allergies or preferences. 'I'd like the chicken, but without onions, please' is normal. In Zimbabwean homes, asking 'without onions' might seem impolite — but in Western restaurants it's expected."},"m07-l05":{"title":"I Like / I Don't Like in English","hook":"Hi! Today: expressing food preferences. 'I love it', 'I don't like ___', 'It's delicious'.","cultural_note":"At an English-speaking dinner party, you may be asked about food preferences and expected to say. Saying 'I love sadza' or 'I don't really eat pork' is normal. Don't fake politeness — directness is preferred over false enthusiasm."},"m07-l06":{"title":"Cooking Verbs in English","hook":"Hi! Cooking verbs: cook, chop, boil. These let you describe how food is made — useful when explaining sadza or stew to an English speaker.","cultural_note":"Many English speakers don't know how sadza is made. When describing it, you can use 'chop the onions, boil the water, then cook the maize meal slowly'. These three basic verbs cover most cooking processes."},"m07-l07":{"title":"Tea, Coffee, Drinks in English","hook":"Hi! Daily drinks order. Tea with milk, black coffee, glass of water. Few words, used constantly.","cultural_note":"British tea culture is strong — 'a cup of tea' is a ritual. Asked 'how do you take it?' (= milk? sugar?), reply clearly: 'White, no sugar' or 'just a splash of milk, two sugars'. American coffee culture leans large and milky, often grabbed on the go."},"m07-l08":{"title":"Sharing Shona Food in English","hook":"Hi! Important lesson. Most English speakers don't know sadza, mufushwa, or mukaranga. You'll be the one explaining — keep the Shona names, just add a brief description.","cultural_note":"Don't translate sadza as 'maize meal porridge' or 'African polenta'. Use the Shona name first, then describe. Other cultures don't translate their food names — kimchi, sushi, paella all keep their original names. Sadza is sadza. Describe its ingredients, taste, and texture."},"m07-l09":{"title":"Hosting in English","hook":"Hi! Welcoming a guest in English: 'Welcome', 'Please, sit down', 'Help yourself'.","cultural_note":"Shona hospitality is very warm — food is served, children are quiet, no one leaves hungry. English hospitality (UK/US) is different: guests are often told 'help yourself' (= take what you want). This can feel cold to a Shona speaker but is actually a sign of trust — they assume you can serve yourself."},"m07-l10":{"title":"A Meal Conversation in English","hook":"Hi! Module 7 capstone: enter the restaurant, order, comment on the food, finish politely. Combine everything in one conversation.","cultural_note":"An English-speaking dinner is built on a few warm phrases: 'please', 'thank you', 'I'd like', 'help yourself'. Shona meal-sharing emphasises generosity; English meal etiquette emphasises ease and pressure-free hosting. Both work — and learning both makes you a better cross-cultural diner."},"m08-l01":{"title":"\"To Be\" & \"To Have\" in English","hook":"In English 'be' and 'have' are foundational. 'I am happy', 'I have a friend' — without these, sentences don't form. Shona 'ndinofara' compresses 'I' and 'am' into one prefix; English keeps them separate.","cultural_note":"Shona prefix 'ndi-' carries the 'I am' or 'I have' meaning. English requires explicit subject ('I') and verb ('am' or 'have'). This isn't English being harder — it's English needing both pieces. Practice until both come automatically."},"m08-l02":{"title":"\"To Do\" & \"To Make\" in English","hook":"In English, 'do' and 'make' look similar but are not interchangeable. 'Do' = complete an existing task (homework, dishes). 'Make' = create something new (tea, food, mistakes).","cultural_note":"Shona 'kuita' covers both meanings. English splits them. 'Make a mistake' (you create the mistake) — never 'do a mistake'. This do/make split is a common stumbling point for Shona speakers learning English. Treat them as two different verbs."},"m08-l03":{"title":"\"To Go\" & \"To Come\" in English","hook":"In English, 'go' = away from speaker; 'come' = toward speaker. When inviting, use 'come' (Come to my house) — from the listener's perspective, you're saying 'come to where I am'.","cultural_note":"Shona 'enda' (go) and 'huya' (come) work the same way. The pivot in English is the speaker's location. 'Are you coming?' — meaning 'are you coming to where I am?'. 'Are you going?' — to somewhere else."},"m08-l04":{"title":"\"To Want\" & \"To Need\" in English","hook":"In English, 'I want' is direct — sometimes too direct in a service context. 'I'd like' (= I would like) is the polite version. 'I need' is reserved for genuine necessities.","cultural_note":"Shona 'ndinoda' covers wanting and needing in any context. In English-speaking restaurants and shops, 'I want' can sound demanding. 'I'd like' is the standard polite form. 'I need' is for emergencies or genuine necessities (I need water)."},"m08-l05":{"title":"Daily Routine — Morning in English","hook":"Good morning! Describing your day in English starts with time: 'at 6', 'at 7'. Then add actions: 'I wake up', 'I take a shower', 'I eat breakfast'.","cultural_note":"Shona 'ndinomuka na6' uses 'na6' for time. English requires 'at 6'. 'At' is a preposition — like Shona's 'pa-' prefix. Phrases like 'wake UP' and 'get UP' have particles ('up') that are part of the verb meaning."},"m08-l06":{"title":"Work & School in English","hook":"In a professional context, your job builds your identity. Use 'I go to work', 'I study English', 'I have a meeting' to describe your day.","cultural_note":"In English, 'I go to work' has no article — never 'I go to the work'. Same with 'school' (I go to school) and 'church' (I go to church). These places are bonded to their activity. But 'meeting' is regular — 'I have A meeting'."},"m08-l07":{"title":"Evening Routine — Coming Home in English","hook":"Evening is wind-down time. In English: 'I come home' (when arriving), 'I cook dinner', 'I watch TV'. Familiar everyday phrases.","cultural_note":"Subtle but important: 'I come home' = arriving home (current speaker location). 'I'm going home' = on the way (not yet there). This 'come' vs 'go' choice depends on where the speaker IS at the time of speaking."},"m08-l08":{"title":"Past Tense in English — Yesterday I...","hook":"Yesterday. In English, past tense usually adds '-ed' (walked, talked). But many common verbs are irregular: 'go' becomes 'went', 'see' becomes 'saw', 'eat' becomes 'ate'. Memorise the irregulars.","cultural_note":"Shona past tense uses prefix 'ndaka-' (ndakaenda = I went) — one prefix, all verbs. English changes the verb itself for many common verbs — irregular forms are unpredictable. Learn the top 20: went, saw, had, was, took, made, came, gave, knew, found, etc."},"m08-l09":{"title":"Future Tense in English — Tomorrow I Will...","hook":"Tomorrow. In English, future uses 'will' or 'going to'. 'I will go' (a decision now). 'I'm going to call' (a plan made earlier). Both work — slight difference.","cultural_note":"Shona future uses prefix 'cha-' (ndichaenda = I will go). English uses 'will' or 'going to'. 'Will' = spontaneous decision; 'going to' = pre-existing plan. 'I'll get it' (spontaneous when phone rings); 'I'm going to call her' (already planned)."},"m08-l10":{"title":"A Day-in-Life Conversation in English","hook":"You finished Module 8. Now combine: 'I am', 'I have', 'I do', 'I make', 'I go', 'I come', 'I want', 'I need', past tense, future. One full day, in English.","cultural_note":"These verb patterns work everywhere English is spoken — London, New York, Cape Town, Lagos, Sydney. Shona compresses with prefixes; English extends with extra words. Both are equally expressive — just different. Once these become automatic, you're functionally fluent in describing daily life."},"m09-l01":{"title":"Where Is...? in English","hook":"Hi! Arriving in London, New York, or any new place — the first phrase you'll need is 'Where is...?'. This unlocks navigation.","cultural_note":"In Zimbabwe, asking for directions can become a long social interaction. In London or NYC, people walk fast — but they're not unfriendly. Approach with 'Excuse me' first, then ask. Locals often take pride in helping with directions in their city."},"m09-l02":{"title":"Left, Right, Straight in English","hook":"Hi! After asking, you'll hear directions. 'Turn left', 'Go straight', 'It's on the right' — these are the words you'll hear.","cultural_note":"In Zimbabwe, directions often come with hand gestures and an offer to walk you part way. In London or NYC, directions are typically brief and verbal: 'Turn left at the lights.' Listen for these short phrases — they'll repeat across many conversations."},"m09-l03":{"title":"How Far? in English","hook":"Hi! After getting a direction, you want to know the distance. 'How far?' tells you whether to walk or grab transport.","cultural_note":"In Zimbabwe, 'far' might mean a half-hour walk; in London, 'far' might mean five minutes. Watch for 'just around the corner' — in English-speaking cities this means very close, often just a minute's walk."},"m09-l04":{"title":"Bus, Taxi, Train in English","hook":"Hi! In Zimbabwe we have kombis. In London they have buses, the tube, and Ubers. The vocabulary differs — but the function is the same.","cultural_note":"In English: 'taxi' = a car (often app-summoned); 'bus' = a large fixed-route vehicle; 'train' = rail transport. London's 'tube' = subway/metro. There's no kombi in London — explain it as 'a small minibus that picks up and drops off whenever you wave'."},"m09-l05":{"title":"Buying a Ticket in English","hook":"Hi! At a station, the train arrives in 20 minutes. You need to buy a ticket. Phrases: 'One ticket to ___, please. Round trip. How much?'","cultural_note":"In the UK and US, train tickets are usually bought before boarding — at machines or counters. 'One-way' = going only; 'return' (UK) or 'round trip' (US) = there and back. Knowing these saves you from buying the wrong ticket."},"m09-l06":{"title":"At the Airport in English","hook":"Hi! The airport — where English really matters. 'Boarding pass', 'departure gate', 'customs' — these get you onto your flight.","cultural_note":"Most airport vocabulary is in English worldwide — 'gate', 'check-in', 'security', 'customs'. At Heathrow or JFK, staff may speak quickly but they're not rude. Ask clearly, and you'll get a clear answer back."},"m09-l07":{"title":"Hotel & Accommodation in English","hook":"Hi! At the hotel: 'I have a reservation', 'My room key', 'I'd like to check out'. These work everywhere — Harare, London, NYC.","cultural_note":"Hotel staff in English-speaking countries often add 'sir' or 'ma'am' — politeness markers. If something's wrong with your room (water, AC, noise), state it clearly and politely: 'There's a problem with the ___'. Staff want to fix it, not argue."},"m09-l08":{"title":"Lost & Travel Emergencies in English","hook":"Hi! Sometimes things go wrong. You miss your bus, lose your bag, get lost in a city. Phrases like 'I'm lost', 'I missed my bus', 'I lost my bag' get you help.","cultural_note":"In Zimbabwe, locals naturally rally around someone in distress. In London or NYC, people are busy — but if you say 'Excuse me, I need help — I'm lost' clearly, most will stop. Adding 'please' shifts you from someone bothering them to someone asking respectfully."},"m09-l09":{"title":"Asking For Help While Travelling in English","hook":"Hi! In a new city, you'll need: 'Could you help me?', 'I don't know this area', 'Could you write it down?'. These open doors.","cultural_note":"In English, polite requests start with 'Could' or 'Would' — softer than 'Can you' (more casual) and 'Help me!' (urgent). 'Could you write it down?' works perfectly with concierges, tour guides, taxi drivers — anyone you might forget directions from."},"m09-l10":{"title":"A Travel Conversation in English","hook":"Hi! Module 9 capstone: ask directions, get directions, ask distance, take transport, buy a ticket, check into a hotel, ask for help. One trip, full English.","cultural_note":"On any trip in an English-speaking country — UK, US, Australia, South Africa — the basic words 'please', 'thank you', 'excuse me', 'could you' carry the whole interaction. They're not optional politeness; they're the lubricant of every transaction. In London or Manhattan, they make the difference between rude and respected."},"m10-l01":{"title":"Happy & Sad in English","hook":"In Shona, emotions often live in the body — 'ndine moyo unorwadza' (my heart hurts). In English, you can be more direct: 'I'm happy', 'I'm sad'.","cultural_note":"It can feel exposing to say 'I'm sad' to someone in English-speaking culture — but it's increasingly normal, especially with therapists, close friends, or family. 'It made me feel...' is a useful phrase to talk about how an event affected you. This direct emotional language is more common in English than Shona."},"m10-l02":{"title":"Anger & Frustration in English","hook":"In English, anger is named directly: 'I'm angry', 'I'm frustrated'. But in workplaces, 'a bit frustrated about ___' is more polished than 'angry'.","cultural_note":"Shona expressions of anger are often somatic and direct — 'mwoyo wangu wakatsva' (my heart is burning). English in workplaces softens to 'a bit frustrated' and adds context ('about the deadline change'). Goal: express the feeling without escalating the conversation."},"m10-l03":{"title":"Fear & Worry in English","hook":"Fear: 'I'm scared' or 'I'm afraid'. Worry: 'I'm worried about ___'. To a close friend, the response 'don't worry' is comforting.","cultural_note":"In English, structure differs: 'I'm worried about ___' (ongoing concern), 'I'm scared of ___' (specific fear). 'Don't worry' alone can sound dismissive — add 'we'll figure it out together' to acknowledge the feeling, not minimise it."},"m10-l04":{"title":"Being Sick in English","hook":"In Shona, you say 'Ndine bambo musoro' (I have a body-part-pain). English uses the same structure: 'I have a headache'. This pattern bridges directly.","cultural_note":"At a UK GP, US doctor, or SA private clinic, your appointment may be only 5-10 minutes. Lead with the symptom, not the whole story: 'I don't feel well. I have a headache that won't go away.' Clarity beats politeness here. 'Won't go away' signals it's persistent — that matters."},"m10-l05":{"title":"Body Parts in English","hook":"Body vocabulary helps with health, descriptions, stories. 'Head', 'stomach', 'arm' — minimal vocabulary, large utility.","cultural_note":"At a physiotherapist abroad, you can point — but words go further. 'It hurts here' works with pointing. Naming the body part ('my lower back hurts') gets faster, more specific care. Bridge: Shona and English share the structure 'My + body part + hurts'."},"m10-l06":{"title":"At the Doctor in English","hook":"Continuing from the last lesson, here's the follow-up: doctor asks 'How long?', 'How bad?', 'What helps?'. Reply with: 'It hurts here', 'For three days', 'Take this medicine'.","cultural_note":"In English, time of duration uses 'for': 'for three days', 'for a week'. Shona 'kwave nemazuva matatu' (it has been three days) is parallel — same idea, just different words. Use clear time markers — doctors will understand quickly."},"m10-l07":{"title":"Telling Past Stories in English","hook":"Stories begin with 'When I was a child...' or 'When I was young...'. Add a memorable element — 'I'll never forget...' — and a feeling: 'It was amazing'.","cultural_note":"Shona oral storytelling is foundational — children hear stories from elders. English-speaking storytelling tends to be shorter (3 sentences) — setting (when), event (what happened), reflection (how it felt). This compact pattern shows up in casual chat and in professional networking."},"m10-l08":{"title":"Hope & Future in English","hook":"In Shona: 'Ndinotarisira', 'Rimwe zuva ndicha...', 'Ndinorota'. In English: 'I hope to...', 'One day I'll...', 'I dream of...'. Many words, one pattern: future + hope.","cultural_note":"In a job interview at an English-speaking company, 'Where do you see yourself in 5 years?' is standard. Soft answer 'I hope to learn and grow' is fine; sharper 'I see myself leading a small team in 5 years' shows ambition. English career English balances 'specific + ambitious + humble'."},"m10-l09":{"title":"Sharing Shona Proverbs in English","hook":"Proverbs are universal — Chinese chéngyǔ, French dictons, English idioms. Today we share three Shona proverbs in English: keep the Shona, translate, then explain meaning.","cultural_note":"When sharing a Shona proverb in English, follow this pattern: (1) Say it in Shona, (2) Give literal translation, (3) Explain the meaning. This honours the original while making it accessible. Other cultures do the same with their proverbs — your Shona wisdom belongs in English-speaking conversations."},"m10-l10":{"title":"Your English Story — A2 Complete","hook":"This is the final lesson. 100 lessons. 10 modules. From 'Hello' to proverbs, from 'My name is...' to job interviews. Today you don't learn — you speak. Your English-learning journey, in English.","cultural_note":"Completing this curriculum means you've crossed into English. You can greet, see a doctor, order in London, hold your own among English speakers, and tell your story. This is the Rwendo journey — from Mhoro to 'Where I'm from we say...'. You opened a door and got English without losing Shona."}}$$::jsonb,
  $${"lesson.continue":"Continue","lesson.back":"Back","lesson.skip":"Skip","lesson.next_phase":"Next","lesson.try_again":"Try again","lesson.well_done":"Well done","lesson.cultural_note":"Cultural note","lesson.target_word":"In English","lesson.native_word":"In your language"}$$::jsonb,
  $${"default_voice_key":"male_warm","voices":[{"key":"male_warm","id":"JBFqnCBsd6RMkjVDRZzb","name":"George","description":"Warm storyteller"},{"key":"male_energy","id":"IKne3meq5aSn9XLyUdCD","name":"Charlie","description":"Energetic, confident"},{"key":"female_warm","id":"cgSgspJ2msm6clMCkdW9","name":"Jessica","description":"Playful, bright, warm"},{"key":"female_clear","id":"Xb7hH8MSUJpSbSDYk0k2","name":"Alice","description":"Clear, engaging educator"}],"greetings":{"morning":{"word":"Good morning","phrase":"Good morning"},"afternoon":{"word":"Good afternoon","phrase":"Good afternoon"},"evening":{"word":"Good evening","phrase":"Good evening"}}}$$::jsonb
)
on conflict (id) do update set
  iso_code       = excluded.iso_code,
  display_name   = excluded.display_name,
  flag_emoji     = excluded.flag_emoji,
  concepts       = excluded.concepts,
  lesson_context = excluded.lesson_context,
  ui_strings     = excluded.ui_strings,
  metadata       = excluded.metadata,
  updated_at     = now();

insert into public.language_packs (id, iso_code, display_name, flag_emoji, concepts, lesson_context, ui_strings, metadata) values (
  'shona',
  'sn',
  'ChiShona',
  '🇿🇼',
